# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: archidendron-jiringa
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] The species is endemic to northern Australia and is adapted to a dry environment.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] The flowers are borne in two spikes in axils on peduncles 3–5 mm (1⁄8–1⁄4 in) long, each spike 30–70 mm (1+1⁄8–2+3⁄4 in) long with golden yellow flowers.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] Flowering occurs from May to September, and the pods are curved or coiled depending on subspecies, thinly leathery to crust-like, 3.5–4 mm (1⁄8–1⁄8 in) wide.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] The seeds are oblong, glossy, very dark brown to black with a bright yellow aril.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] McDonald and Bruce Maslin described var.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] It is well adapted to an arid environment and is found in a variety of habitats including stony hills and ridges, sandplains, floodplains and along drainage lines growing in stony, sandy, clay-loam soils.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] Variety *ileocarpa* has a scattered distribution in the southern Kimberley region and adjacent parts of western Northern Territory, and a restricted distribution in the Pilbara region.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] Its uses include environmental management, forage, and wood.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] The seeds have a good taste and can be eaten raw, cooked, or ground into flour.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] The results of tests in Nigeria for the feasibility of raising the tree as a drought-resistant food crop came out very positively.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] There are some recent reports that up to 1.8% dimethyltryptamine (DMT) is present in the bark of *Acacia colei*.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-colei] The Walmadjari people in the Kimberley call this wattle, **parta**, the Djaru people call it **barrawi** or **barrabi**.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] A natural colonizer, Coojong tends to grow wherever soil has been disturbed, such as alongside new roads.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] Its seeds are distributed by ants, which store them in their nests to eat the seed-stalks.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] Disturbance of the soil brings them to the surface and allows them to germinate.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] Seeds germinate readily, and hundreds of seedlings can sometimes be found beneath a single parent tree.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] It is also extremely vigorous when young, often growing over a metre per year.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] It was planted in the northern suburbs of Sydney in the 1950s, and has subsequently become a major weed in eastern New South Wales, Victoria and South Australia.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] Since 2019, the species is included on the list of invasive alien species of Union concern.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] This means that the species can no longer be imported in the European Union.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] Additionally, it has become illegal to plant it, breed it, transport it, or bring it into the wild.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] In South Africa, it proliferated at an uncontrollable rate, having been introduced in the nineteenth century to produce tan bark and to stabilise the sands of the Cape Flats outside Cape Town after the indigenous bush had largely been cut down for firewood.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] In addition to replacing indigenous fynbos vegetation, it also hampers agriculture.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] It is listed as an invasive alien plant in the Cape Floristic Region of South Africa, where it has displaced native species through changing fire regimes.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] The introduction of the acacia gall rust fungus, (*Uromycladium tepperianum*), has proven to be highly effective at reining it in, reducing density by 80%.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-saligna] The acacia seed weevil (*Melanterius* species) was introduced in 2001 and has now (in 2007) reached the stage where there are sufficient numbers available to begin its distribution.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] The openly branched spreading tree or shrub typically grows to a height of 5 to 15 metres (16 to 49 ft) with a well developed canopy.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] It has hard grey glossy bark that is occasionally fissured with pruinose orange to yellow branchlets.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] It has falcate to subfalcate glaucous green phyllodes that are 6 to 25 centimetres (2 to 10 in) long and 0.7 to 6 cm (0.3 to 2.4 in) wide.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] It produces between April and October and produces yellow inflorescences, usually racemose or axillary or terminal panicles 20 cm (7.9 in) long.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] These eventually develop into narrow oblong woody glabrous seed pods that are 3 to 12 cm (1.2 to 4.7 in) in length containing glossy black seeds.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] It is also cultivated in Yemen, Vietnam, Senegal and Niger.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] Indigenous Australians used the trunk of young trees to fashion spears and boomerangs.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] The green seed pods were cooked over coals and the seeds then eaten.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] Fully ripened black seeds were ground into flour mixed with water and consumed as a paste or cooked and eaten as a damper.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] Other traditional uses include making string from the bark and using the gum exudate as a food source.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] It is cultivated in Senegal and Niger, where it is used as good quality firewood and to create low windbreaks.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/acacia-tumida] It is also used with slower growing plants for binding soil.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Standard **anatomical terms of location** are used to describe unambiguously the anatomy of humans and other animals.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The terms, typically derived from Latin or Greek roots, describe something in its standard anatomical position.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] This position provides a definition of what is at the front ("anterior"), behind ("posterior") and so on.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] As part of defining and describing terms, the body is described through the use of anatomical planes and axes.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The meaning of terms that are used can change depending on whether a vertebrate is a biped or a quadruped, due to the difference in the neuraxis, or if an invertebrate is a non-bilaterian.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] A non-bilaterian has no anterior or posterior surface for example but can still have a descriptor used such as proximal or distal in relation to a body part that is nearest to, or furthest from its middle.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] International organisations have determined vocabularies that are often used as standards for subdisciplines of anatomy.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For example, *Terminologia Anatomica*, *Terminologia Neuroanatomica*, and *Terminologia Embryologica* for humans and *Nomina Anatomica Veterinaria* for animals.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] These allow parties that use anatomical terms, such as anatomists, veterinarians, and medical doctors, to have a standard set of terms to communicate clearly the position of a structure.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Much of this information has been standardised in internationally agreed vocabularies for humans (*Terminologia Anatomica*, *Terminologia Neuroanatomica*, and *Terminologia Embryologica*), with *Nomina Anatomica Veterinaria* and *Nomina Embryologica Veterinaria* used for animal anatomy.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Different terms are used for those vertebrates that are bipedal and those that are quadrupedal.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The reasoning is that the neuraxis, and therefore the standard anatomical position is different between the two groups.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Unique terms are also used to describe invertebrates, because of their wider variety of shapes and symmetries.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] This helps to avoid confusion in terminology when referring to the same animal in different postures.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In humans, this refers to the body in a standing position with arms at the side and palms facing forward.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In quadrupeds this is an animal standing upright with all four feet on the ground and the head facing forward.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For a fish this is belly down with neutral appendages.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Anatomical terms describe structures with relation to three main anatomical planes.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Anatomical planes are useful in a number of fields including medical imaging, embryology, and the study of movement.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Sagittal planes and transverse planes are used as anatomical lines to delineate bodily regions.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] There are several transverse planes with clinical relevance in the division of the torso into sections.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] They include the transpyloric plane, the subcostal plane, and the transumbilical plane.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The three axes of a vertebrate, are formed in embryonic development before and during the gastrulation stage.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Distinct ends of the embryo are chosen, and the axis is named according to those directions.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The three main axes of a bilaterally symmetrical animal that intersect at right angles, are the left-right, the craniocaudal, and the anteroposterior axes.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] An organism that is round, or asymmetrical may have different axes.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In the standard human anatomical position, **superior** (from Latin *super* 'above') or **cranial**, describes something that is nearer to the head, and **inferior** (from Latin *inferus* 'below') or **caudal** describes what is below, and nearer to the feet.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Examples are the superior mediastinum, and inferior mediastinum.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Neuroanatomy examples are the superior colliculus, and the inferior colliculus.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In veterinary anatomy, the terms superior and inferior are not used except to describe the eye, eyelids, lips and inner ear, using instead **dorsal** and **ventral**.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] These two terms, used in veterinary anatomy, are also used in human anatomy mostly in neuroanatomy, and embryology, to describe something at the back (dorsal, posterior) or front (ventral, anterior) of an organ, or organism.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The **dorsal** (from Latin *dorsum* 'back') surface, (also **dorsum**) of an organism or organ, refers to the back, or upper side, such as in the human, the dorsum of the tongue, the dorsum of the hand, and the dorsum of the foot.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] If talking about the skull, the dorsal side is the top.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The **ventral** (from Latin *venter* 'belly') surface refers to the front, or lower side, of an organism, or organ such as the undersurface of the tongue.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In a fish, the dorsal fin is on the upper surface and its ventral fins (pelvic fins) are on the belly or undersurface.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The terms are used in other contexts, for example in dorsal and ventral gun turrets on a bomber aircraft.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] These terms describe how close something is to the median plane.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] **Lateral** (from Latin *lateralis* 'to the side') describes something to the sides of an animal, as in "left lateral" and "right lateral".
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] **Medial** (from Latin *medius* 'middle') describes structures close to the median plane, or closer to the median plane than another structure.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For example, in a human, the arms are lateral to the torso.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] **Temporal** has a similar meaning to lateral but is restricted to the head.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The terms "left" and "right", or sinistral and dextral, refer to the halves of a bilaterally symmetrical body divided by the median plane.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The terms **proximal** (from Latin *proximus* 'nearest') and **distal** (from Latin *distare* 'to stand away from') are used to describe parts of a feature that are close to or distant from the main mass of the body, respectively.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Thus the upper arm in humans is proximal and the hand is distal.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The main mass is taken as the center, the chest, or the heart.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] "Proximal and distal" are frequently used when describing appendages, such as fins, tentacles, and limbs.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Although the direction indicated by "proximal" and "distal" is always respectively towards or away from the point of attachment, a given structure can be either proximal or distal in relation to another point of reference.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Thus the elbow is distal to a wound on the upper arm, but proximal to a wound on the lower arm.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] This terminology is also employed in molecular biology and therefore by extension is also used in chemistry, specifically referring to the atomic loci of molecules from the overall moiety of a given compound.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Specific terms exist to describe how close or far something is to the head or tail of an animal.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] These terms are generally preferred in veterinary medicine and not used as often in human medicine.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For example, in horses, the eyes are caudal to the nose and rostral to the back of the head.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In humans, "cranial" and "cephalic" are used to refer to the skull, with "cranial" being used more commonly.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The term "rostral" is rarely used in human gross anatomy and refers more to the front of the face than the superior aspect of the organism.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] But it is used in embryology, and neuroanatomy.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Similarly, the term "caudal" is used more in embryology and neuroanatomy, and only occasionally in human gross anatomy.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The "rostrocaudal axis" refers to the curved line of the neuraxis from the forehead (rostral) towards the tail end (caudal).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Central and peripheral refer to the distance towards and away from the centre of something.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] That might be an organ, a region in the body, or an anatomical structure.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For example, the central nervous system and the peripheral nervous systems.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] These terms refer to the distance of a structure from the surface.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Many anatomical terms can be combined, either to indicate a position in two axes simultaneously or to indicate the direction of a movement relative to the body.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For example, **anterolateral** indicates a position that is both anterior and lateral to the body axis (such as the bulk of the pectoralis major muscle), or to a named organ such as the anterolateral tibial tubercle.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The term can also describe the direction and location of something that enters or courses through the body such as the anterolateral system in the spinal cord, and the anterolateral central arteries.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Another term **anteromedial** is used for example in the anteromedial central arteries.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In the more internal brain and spinal cord of the central nervous system the terms dorsal and ventral and their combinations are often used in place of anterior and posterior.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In these organs numerous references need to be used, and in the brain for example the prefrontal cortex has the divisions of the dorsomedial prefrontal cortex, and the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] And the dorsomedial region has subcompartments that make use of other terms such as the anterior cingulate cortex, and infralimbic cortex.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Structures such as the anterior cingulate cortex may be divided anatomically based on cognitive (dorsal), and emotional (ventral) components.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In radiology, various X-ray views uses terminology based on where the X-ray beam enters and leaves the body, including the front to back view (**anteroposterior**), the back to front view (**posteroanterior**), and the side view (**lateral**).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Combined terms were once generally hyphenated, but typically the hyphen is omitted.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The location of anatomical structures can also be described in relation to different anatomical landmarks used in anatomy, surface anatomy, surgery, and radiology.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Structures may be described as being at the level of a specific vertebra, depending on the section of the vertebral column the structure is at.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For example, structures at the level of the fourth cervical vertebra may be abbreviated as "C4", at the level of the fourth thoracic vertebra "T4", and at the level of the third lumbar vertebra "L3".
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Because the sacrum and coccyx are fused, they are not often used to provide the location.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] References may also take origin from surface anatomy, made to landmarks that are on the skin or visible underneath.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For example, structures may be described relative to the anterior superior iliac spine, the medial malleolus or the medial epicondyle.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Anatomical lines are theoretical lines, using either horizontal transverse planes, or vertical sagittal planes, used to describe anatomical location.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For examples, the mid-clavicular line is used as part of the cardiac examination to feel the apex beat of the heart, and the axillary lines are reference lines for the underarm region.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Other types of lines in anatomy include the curved nuchal lines on the occipital bone, and the gluteal lines on the ilium.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Special terms are used to describe the mouth and teeth.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Fields such as osteology, paleontology and dentistry apply special terms of location to describe the mouth and teeth.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] This is because although teeth may be aligned with their main axes within the jaw, some different relationships require special terminology as well; for example, teeth also can be rotated, and in such contexts terms like "anterior" or "lateral" become ambiguous.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For example, the terms "distal" and "proximal" (or "mesial") are used for surfaces of individual teeth relative to the midpoint of the dental arch, and "medial" and "lateral" are used in the standard sense relative to the median plane.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Terms used to describe structures include "buccal" (from Latin *bucca* 'cheek') and "palatal" (from Latin *palatum* 'palate') referring to structures close to the cheek and hard palate respectively.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Several anatomical terms are particular to the hands and feet.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Additional terms may be used to avoid confusion when describing the surfaces of the hand and what is the "anterior" or "posterior" surface.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The term "anterior", while anatomically correct, can be confusing when describing the palm of the hand; Similarly is "posterior", used to describe the back of the hand and arm.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] This confusion can arise because the forearm can pronate and supinate and flip the location of the hand.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For improved clarity, the directional term **palmar** (from Latin *palma* 'palm of the hand') is commonly used to describe the front of the hand, and **dorsal** is the back of the hand.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The palmar fascia is *palmar* to the tendons of muscles which flex the fingers, and the dorsal venous arch is so named because it is on the dorsal side of the foot.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In humans, **volar** can also be used synonymously with *palmar* to refer to the palm of the hand, and can also be used to refer to the sole of the foot.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] But *palmar* is used exclusively for the palm of the hand, and **plantar** is used exclusively for the sole of the foot.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Similarly, in the limbs for clarity, the sides are named after the bones.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In the forearm, structures closer to the radius are **radial**, structures closer to the ulna are **ulnar**, and structures relating to both bones are referred to as **radioulnar**, such as the distal radioulnar joint.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Similarly, in the lower leg, structures near the tibia (shinbone) are **tibial** and structures near the fibula are **fibular** (or **peroneal**).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Several other terms are also used to describe location.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] These terms are not used to form the fixed axes.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Different terms are used because of different body plans in animals, whether animals stand on two or four legs, and whether an animal is symmetrical or asymmetrical.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] For example, as humans are bilaterally symmetrical, anatomical descriptions usually use the same terms as those for other vertebrates.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] However, the standard human anatomical position means that their anterior/posterior and ventral/dorsal directions are the same, so the inferior/superior directions are used due to longstanding tradition instead of cranial/caudal, which apply regardless of position, as in other species.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Flounder and other flatfish which lie on the seabed on their left or right side are asymmetric, with both eyes on the 'up' side, making anatomical nomenclature a challenge.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Invertebrates have a large variety of body shapes that can present a problem when trying to apply standard directional terms.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Depending on the organism, some terms are taken by analogy from vertebrate anatomy, and appropriate novel terms are applied as needed.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Some such borrowed terms are widely applicable in most invertebrates; for example proximal, meaning "near" refers to the part of an appendage nearest to where it joins the body, and distal, meaning "standing away from" is used for the part furthest from the point of attachment.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In all cases, the usage of terms is dependent on the body plan of the organism.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In non-bilaterian organisms with a changeable shape, such as amoeboid organisms, most directional terms are meaningless, since the shape of the organism is not constant and no distinct axes are fixed.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Similarly, in radially symmetrical organisms, there is nothing to distinguish one line through the centre of the organism from any other.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] An indefinite number of triads of mutually perpendicular axes could be defined, but any such choice of axes would be useless, as nothing would distinguish a chosen triad from any others.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In such organisms, only terms such as *superficial* and *deep*, or sometimes *proximal* and *distal*, are usefully descriptive.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In organisms that maintain a constant shape and have one dimension longer than the other, at least two directional terms can be used.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The *long* or *longitudinal axis* is defined by points at the opposite ends of the organism.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Similarly, a perpendicular *transverse axis* can be defined by points on opposite sides of the organism.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] There is typically no basis for the definition of a third axis.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Usually such organisms are planktonic (free-swimming) protists, and are nearly always viewed on microscope slides, where they appear essentially two-dimensional.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In some cases a third axis can be defined, particularly where a non-terminal cytostome or other unique structure is present.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Some elongated protists have distinctive ends of the body.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] In such organisms, the end with a mouth (or equivalent structure, such as the cytostome in *Paramecium* or *Stentor*), or the end that usually points in the direction of the organism's locomotion (such as the end with the flagellum in *Euglena*), is normally designated as the **anterior** end.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The opposite end then becomes the **posterior end**.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Properly, this terminology would apply only to an organism that is always planktonic (not normally attached to a surface), although the term can also be applied to one that is sessile (normally attached to a surface).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Organisms that are attached to a substrate, such as sponges and animal-like protists also have distinctive ends.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] The part of the organism attached to the substrate is usually referred to as the **basal end** (from Latin *basis* 'support/foundation'), whereas the end furthest from the attachment is referred to as the **apical end** (from Latin *apex* 'peak/tip').
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Radially symmetrical organisms include those in the group Radiata – primarily Cnidarians (jellyfish, sea anemones and corals, and the comb jellies).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Adult echinoderms, such as starfish, sea urchins, sea cucumbers and others are also included, since they have a pentamerous symmetry having five discrete symmetric parts arranged around a central axis.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Echinoderm larvae are not included, since they are bilaterally symmetrical.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Cnidarians have an incomplete digestive system, meaning that one end of the organism has a mouth, the **oral end** (from Latin *ōrālis* 'of the mouth'), and the opposite **aboral end** (from Latin *ab-* 'away from') has no opening from the gut (coelenteron).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] They are radially symmetric around the **oral-aboral axis**.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Having only the single distinctive axis, "lateral", "dorsal", and "ventral" have no meaning, and all can be replaced by the generic term **peripheral** (from Ancient Greek *περιφέρεια* 'circumference').
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] **Medial** can be used, but in the case of radiates indicates the central point, rather than a central axis as in vertebrates.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Thus, there are multiple possible **radial axes** and **medio-peripheral** (half-) **axes**.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Comb jellies have a biradial symmetry about only two planes, a tentacular plane, and a pharyngeal plane.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Two such terms are useful in describing views of the legs and pedipalps of spiders, and other arachnids.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] **Prolateral** refers to the surface of a leg that is closest to the anterior end of an arachnid's body.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] **Retrolateral** refers to the surface of a leg that is closest to the posterior end of an arachnid's body.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Most spiders have eight eyes in four pairs.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] All the eyes are on the carapace of the prosoma, and their sizes, shapes and locations are characteristic of various spider families and other taxa.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Usually, the eyes are arranged in two roughly parallel, horizontal and symmetrical rows of eyes.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/anatomical-terms-of-location] Eyes are labelled according to their position as anterior and posterior lateral eyes (ALE) and (PLE); and anterior and posterior median eyes (AME) and (PME).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Common English names are blackbead, dog fruit, *jengkol* tree, *luk nieng* tree and *ngapi* nut.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] As this plant grows in different countries in Southeast Asia, it has a variety of vernacular names.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The common names in Indonesia is *jengkol*, *jinkol*, *jarung* (Sumatra) or *jering* (Java).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] It is called *krakos* in Cambodia, *jering* in Malaysia, and Thailand.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Other vernacular names include *luk nieng*, *cha niang*, *khang daeng* and *pha niang*.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] In Myanmar it is called *da-nyin-thee* or *da-nyin-pen*.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The fruit (legume) of the tree is a woody, glabrous, deep purple pod.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Each Pod contains around three to nine round-shaped seeds.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The pods are formed falcate or twisted in a wide spiral.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The seed coat of a young seed shows a yellow-green colour and turns dark brown during ripening.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Then the ripe fruit dehisces along the ventral suture.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The tree is indigenous to primary and secondary forests in humid, mountainous, and undulating areas as well as on river banks from sea level up to 1600 m elevation in Southeast Asian countries such as Bangladesh, Indonesia (Sumatra, Sulawesi, Kalimantan), Malaysia, Myanmar, and Southern Thailand.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Djenkol trees grow best in pervious sandy or lateritic soils and they need a high rainfall guarantee.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The Djenkol fruit contains djenkolic acid.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Eating the djenkol fruit is linked to cases of hematuria.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] In a study of school children aged 7-11 in Hat-Yai, Thailand who had hematuria, the children were almost four times as likely to have a history of eating djenkol beans.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] In the cases of eating djenkol, increasing consumption, time since last consumption, or type of preparation (even after adjustment for sex and age) did not change the risk of having hematuria.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] In that same study, the conclusion was derived that eating djenkol beans may be defined as one of the probable causes of hematuria.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] In another report from Indonesia, djenkol consumption can cause hypersaturation of djenkolic acid crystals within the urinary system.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] That leads to obstructive nephropathy with sludge, stones, or possible spasms.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] In this report, 96 cases of djenkolism were identified.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Recovery for the majority of patients included using hydration, bicarbonate therapy, and pain medication for treatment.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Another patient had obstructing djenkolic acid stones and required urethral stinting.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Out of the 96 reported cases, four patients died with the final diagnosis as acute kidney failure.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] In a different study of Australian acacia seeds (*Acacia colei, Acacia elecantha, Acacia tumida*, and *Acacia saligna*), the study focused on processing methods to reduce djenkolic acid in the seeds.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The study tested the levels of djenkolic acid in the seeds of each species and reported the levels to be similar to the djenkol bean.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The conclusion of that study surmised that djenkolic acid levels can be reduced by over 90% through dry roasting at 180°C.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The new lower levels of djenkolic acid were safe for human consumption.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] However, in the Hat-Yai, Thailand study, different types of preparation did not change the risk of having hematuria.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The beans of the djenkol tree have a crude carbohydrate content of about 26% which is relatively low compared to other common legumes, such as cowpea, kidney bean, and pea which all contain about 60 - 70%.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The crude protein content instead is about 14.2%.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] This is higher than that of common cereals, such as wheat (13%), rye (11%), or rice (7%).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The presence of adequate protein and low-fat contents might be perceived as desirable by consumers.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] When processed to flour, high moisture content (about 59%) suggests that this seed needs to be further processed to improve its shelf life and overall quality.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Djenkol beans are 3.0 to 3.5 cm in diameter and 1.5 to 2.0 cm thick and have a reddish-brown color.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] These beans are prepared by frying, boiling, or roasting and are also eaten raw.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] They are mainly consumed in Thailand, Malaysia, Myanmar, and Indonesia.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The seeds of djenkol are mainly used to add flavour to food, although the crushed seeds give off a mild sulfurous odor which is perceived as rather offensive by some people.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Young seeds are often eaten raw as so-called ulam.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Different parts of the djenkol tree are applied in traditional medicine in Southeast Asia.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The raw seeds are thought to purify the blood or cure dysentery.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Compresses with young leaves are used for skin problems, and burnt old leaves are believed to relieve itchy feelings.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The powder of burnt young leaves is applied to cuts and wounds.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Djenkol trees have often been spared when primary or secondary rainforests have been cut down.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Otherwise planting distances are 10–15 m.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The plant favours well-drained sandy, lateritic or sandy clay soil. is propagated by Seed.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Methods for clonal distribution have not yet been found.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] In nature, squirrels (*Callosciurus notatus*) eat the seeds and facilitate their distribution.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] A tree produces between 1000 and 4000 seeds per year.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] The main harvesting time in Java is around July to August and the aftercrop in December to February.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Usually, djenkol is sold in the markets by several seeds.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] For transport, seeds, in particular young ones, should not be removed from the pods to avoid desiccation.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] One way to store the seeds is by processing them into chips (emping).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] Another possibility however could be its procession to flour.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron-jiringa] To date, due to the high moisture content, this is hardly done.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron] Plants in this genus are shrubs or small to medium-sized trees up to 30 metres (98 ft) tall; they have bipinnate leaves, extrafloral nectaries, and without spines or thorns.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron] Leaflets are usually arranged in opposite pairs.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron] The genus is morphologically diverse in the characters of leaves, flowers and fruit.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron] Inflorescence position may be *axillary*, *terminal*, ramiflorous or cauliflorous.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron] The form may be a 'head' or capitulum, an umbel, a raceme or a panicle.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron] Flowers may be bell-shaped or tubular, the calyx and the corolla tube both 5-lobed.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron] There are numerous stamens and one to several carpels.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron] The fruit is a pod which may be flat, cylindrical, or twisted.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/archidendron] As of December 2024, Plants of the World Online accepts the following 98 species, while another 20 species are yet to be formally described.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/australian-plant-name-index] The **Australian Plant Name Index** (**APNI**) is an online database of all published names of Australian vascular plants.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/australian-plant-name-index] It covers all names, whether current names, synonyms or invalid names.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/australian-plant-name-index] It includes bibliographic and typification details, information from the Australian Plant Census including distribution by state, links to other resources such as specimen collection maps and plant photographs, and the facility for notes and comments on other aspects.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/australian-plant-name-index] Originally the brainchild of Nancy Tyson Burbidge, it began as a four-volume printed work consisting of 3,055 pages and containing over 60,000 plant names.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/australian-plant-name-index] Compiled by Arthur Chapman, it was part of the Australian Biological Resources Study (ABRS).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/australian-plant-name-index] In 1991 it was made available as an online database and handed over to the Australian National Botanic Gardens.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/australian-plant-name-index] Two years later, responsibility for its maintenance was given to the newly formed Centre for Plant Biodiversity Research.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The territory of modern Bangladesh was a stronghold of many Hindu and Buddhist dynasties in ancient history.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Following the Muslim conquest in 1204, the region saw Sultanate and Mughal rule.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] As the largest subdivision of the Mughal Empire, the region of Bengal emerged one of the most prosperous and commercially active areas of the world, known for its thriving textile industry and agricultural productivity.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Battle of Plassey in 1757 marked the beginning of British colonial rule for the following two centuries.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The period experienced immense flight of capital which was used to finance the industrial revolution in Great Britain while Bengal was devastated by periods of deadly famines.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In the aftermath of the Partition of India in 1947, East Bengal became the eastern and most populous wing of the newly formed Dominion of Pakistan and was later renamed to East Pakistan.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Following over two decades of political repression and systemic racism from the West Pakistan–based government, East Pakistan experienced civil unrest with the 1971 non-cooperation movement, which led to the Bangladesh Liberation War following a violent government military operation.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Mukti Bahini, with aid and assistance from Indian forces, waged a successful armed revolution; and, despite the Bangladesh genocide carried out by Pakistan, Bangladesh became a sovereign nation on 16 December 1971.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Post-Independence, Sheikh Mujibur Rahman led the country until his assassination in 1975.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Presidency was later transferred to Ziaur Rahman, who himself was assassinated in 1981.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The 1980s were dominated by the dictatorship of Hussain Muhammad Ershad, who was overthrown in a mass uprising in 1990.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Following the democratisation in 1991, the Battle of the Begums between Khaleda Zia and Sheikh Hasina defined the country's politics for the next 34 years.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Hasina was overthrown in a mass uprising on 5 August 2024.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is a unitary parliamentary republic based on the Westminster system.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It is a middle power with the second-largest economy in South Asia.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is home to the fourth-largest Muslim population in the world.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It maintains the third-largest military in South Asia and is the largest contributor to the peacekeeping operations of the United Nations.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh consists of eight divisions, 64 districts, 500 sub-districts, and 4,599 union councils, and is home to the largest mangrove forest in the world.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It has one of the largest refugee populations in the world and continues to face challenges such as endemic corruption, human rights abuses, political instability, and adverse effects of climate change.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is a member state of SAARC and several other international organisations.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The etymology of *Bangladesh* ("Bengali country") can be traced to the early 20th century, when Bengali patriotic songs, such as *Aaji Bangladesher Hridoy* by Rabindranath Tagore and *Namo Namo Namo Bangladesh Momo* by Kazi Nazrul Islam, used the term in 1905 and 1932 respectively.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Starting in the 1950s, Bengali nationalists used the term in political rallies in East Pakistan.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The term *Bangla* can refer to both the Bengal region and the Bengali language.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The origins of the term *Bangla* are unclear, with theories pointing to a Bronze Age proto-Dravidian tribe, and the Iron Age Vanga Kingdom.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The earliest known usage of the term is the Nesari plate in 805 AD.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The term *Vangala Desa* is found in 11th-century South Indian records.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The term gained official status during the Sultanate of Bengal in the 14th century.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Shamsuddin Ilyas Shah proclaimed himself as the first "Shah of Bangala" in 1342.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The word *Bangāl* became the most common name for the region during the Islamic period.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Sixteenth century historian Abu'l-Fazl ibn Mubarak mentions in his *Ain-i-Akbari* that the addition of the suffix *"al"* came from the fact that the ancient rajahs of the land raised mounds of earth in lowlands at the foot of the hills which were called "al".
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] This is also mentioned in Ghulam Husain Salim's Riyaz-us-Salatin.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Indo-Aryan suffix *Desh* is derived from the Sanskrit word *deśha*, which means "land" or "country".
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Hence, the name *Bangladesh* means "Land of Bengal" or "Country of Bengal".
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The first great indigenous empire to cover the territory was the Maurya Empire (c.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Following its decline, the kingdom of Samatata arose, which was a tributary state of the Gupta Empire (ca.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Harsha (606–47 AD) drew Samatata into its loosely administered political structure.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Buddhist Pala Empire ruled the region from 750 to 1150 AD.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It was overthrown by the Hindu Sena dynasty, which ruled the territory until the Muslim conquests led by Muhammad Bakhtiyar Khalji of the Ghurid dynasty in 1204.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bengal Sultanate era Mosque architecture.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bengal was then incorporated into the Delhi Sultanate (1206–1526 AD).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In 1341, the independent Bengal Sultanate was established by Fakhruddin Mubarak Shah.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Two dynasties ruled the independent Sultanate of Bengal consecutively, the Hussain Shahi dynasty and the Ilyas Shahi dynasty, with a brief reign of the House of Ganesha.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Amidst geographic expansion and economic prosperity, it was regarded by European and Chinese visitors as the "richest country to trade with".
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Mughal Empire conquered Bengal in 1576.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] By the 18th century, the Bengal Subah emerged as the wealthiest province of the empire and was described as the "Paradise of Countries" and the "breadbasket of India".
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Its citizens maintained some of the best standards of living in the world, as the region was a major global exporter and producer of cotton textiles (muslin in particular), silk and shipbuilding.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Following the decline of the Mughal Empire in the early 1700s, the region became a semi-independent state under the Nawabs of Bengal, founded by Murshid Quli Khan in 1717.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] On 23 June 1757, the state led by Siraj-ud-Daulah was defeated by the British East India Company in the Battle of Plassey—which was key in establishing colonial British rule over Bengal and the wider Indian subcontinent.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bengal played a crucial role in the Industrial Revolution at the expense of an extraordinary capital flight and deindustrialisation following British colonial loot and the collapse of the Bengali textile industry.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The catastrophic Great Bengal famine of 1770 caused between one ten million deaths, killing up to one-third of the total population of the Bengal Presidency.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The western and eastern wings of the newly formed Pakistan were geographically separated by a distance of over 1,000 miles, which became the root cause of deep economic inequality.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Khawaja Nazimuddin was East Bengal's first chief minister with Frederick Chalmers Bourne its governor.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The All Pakistan Awami Muslim League was formed in 1949.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In 1950, the East Bengal Legislative Assembly enacted land reform, abolishing the Permanent Settlement and the zamindari system.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Awami Muslim League was renamed as a more "secular" Awami League in 1953.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The first constituent assembly was dissolved in 1954.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Fazlul Huq swept aside the Muslim League in a landslide victory in the 1954 East Bengali legislative election.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] East Bengal was renamed East Pakistan in 1956 as part of the One Unit Scheme under the new constitution, and the province became a vital part of the Southeast Asia Treaty Organization.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Amidst rising cultural and societal differences, the brutal government crackdown on the 1952 Bengali language movement to establish Bengali as the official language of Pakistan spurred Bengali nationalism and pro-democracy movements.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Pakistan adopted a new constitution in 1956.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Pakistan Armed Forces imposed martial law in 1958, following a coup d'état, with Ayub Khan establishing a dictatorship for over a decade.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] A new constitution was introduced in 1962, replacing the parliamentary system with a presidential and gubernatorial system (based on electoral college selection) known as "Basic Democracy".
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In 1962, Dhaka became the seat of the National Assembly of Pakistan, a move seen as appeasing increased Bengali nationalism.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In 1966, Awami League leader Sheikh Mujibur Rahman announced a six-point movement for a federal parliamentary democracy.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Ethnic, linguistic, and cultural discrimination was common in Pakistan's civil and military services, in which Bengalis were under-represented; leading to East Pakistan forging a distinct political identity.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Authorities banned Bengali literature and music in the state media.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Pakistani government practised extensive economic discrimination against East Pakistan, including the refusal for foreign aid allocation.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Despite generating 70% of Pakistan's export revenue with jute and tea, East Pakistan received much less government spending.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Notable economists from East Pakistan, including Rehman Sobhan and Nurul Islam demanded a separate foreign exchange account for the eastern wing, also pointing to the existence of two different economies within Pakistan itself, dubbed the Two-Economies Theory.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The populist leader Sheikh Mujibur Rahman was arrested for treason in the Agartala Conspiracy Case and was released during the 1969 uprising in East Pakistan which resulted in Ayub Khan's resignation.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] General Yahya Khan assumed power, reintroducing martial law.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] After the December 1970 elections, the Bengali-nationalist Awami League won 167 of 169 East Pakistani seats in the National Assembly.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The League claimed the right to form a government and develop a new constitution but was strongly opposed by the Pakistani military and the Pakistan Peoples Party led by Zulfikar Ali Bhutto.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The 7 March Speech of Mujib led to a non-cooperation movement.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The autocratic Pakistani government then initiated Operation Searchlight on 25 March 1971 in response.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] While Mujib was arrested by the Pakistani Army on 26 March 1971, freedom fighter Major Ziaur Rahman publicly broadcast the independence of Bangladesh on behalf of Mujib.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] A nine-month-long bloody liberation war ensued, during which a genocide of ethnic Bengalis occurred.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The culmination of the war established Bangladesh as a sovereign nation following Pakistani surrender on 16 December 1971.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Constitution of Bangladesh was enacted on 4 November 1972.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Following independence, the Mujib-led government engaged in large-scale corruption and mismanagement, leading to nationwide lawlessness and economic devastation.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Efforts to establish One-party socialism and a large famine in 1974 led to Mujib's assassination in 1975 following a significant decline in his popularity.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The presidency was then transferred to Ziaur Rahman, who re-established public order, industrialised agriculture, founded the Bangladesh Nationalist Party and initiated the creation of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Ziaur Rahman founded the Bangladesh Nationalist Party on September 1, 1978.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Following Rahman's assassination in 1981, the ensuing decade was a military dictatorship under Hussain Muhammad Ershad that saw infrastructural development, devolution reforms, privatisation of nationalised industries and the declaration of Islam as the state religion in 1988.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] After the restoration of parliamentary democracy in 1991, power alternated between Khaleda Zia of the BNP and Sheikh Hasina of the Awami League, an era dubbed the Battle of Begums—which defined Bangladesh's politics and history for 34 years until 2024.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Following the return of the Awami League to power after the 2008 general election.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The country under Sheikh Hasina's leadership saw economic progress but also witnessed democratic backsliding, increasing authoritarianism, endemic corruption, and widespread human rights abuses.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] According to various reports Hasina and the Awami League Government, aided by cooperation with India, organized the 2009 Bangladesh Rifles revolt to kill capable army officers whom Hasina deemed a threat to her power destabilizing the Bangladesh Army and solidifying de facto one party rule.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Hasina won her second, third and fourth consecutive terms in the 2014, 2018 and the 2024 general elections—all of which were shams and neither free nor fair.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Following a July Uprising against the authoritarian government, Hasina was forced to resign and flee to India on 5 August 2024.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] An interim government was formed in August 2024, with Nobel laureate Muhammad Yunus as the Chief Adviser.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] After the 2026 general election the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) returned to power with Chairman Tarique Rahman being inaugurated as the Prime Minister of Bangladesh on 17 February 2026.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh Jamaat-e-Islami became the main opposition party.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Since the early 1990s, driven by free market policies and economic liberalisation measures, Bangladesh has achieved significant economic growth—emerging as one of the fastest-growing economies in the world, driven by its large textile industry, which is the second-largest in the world.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It has emerged as the second-largest economy in South Asia, surpassing the nominal GDP per capita of neighboring India since 2018.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh has achieved remarkable feats in reducing its poverty rate, which has gone down from 80% in 1971, to 44.2% in 1991, and all the way down to 18.7% in 2022.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Its Human Development Index growth during the 21st century was surpassed only by China.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] As part of the green transition, Bangladesh's industrial sector emerged as a leader in building green factories, with the country having the largest number of certified green factories in the world.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It has also given shelter to over a million Rohingya refugees fleeing the Rohingya genocide since 2017, which has strained its resources and highlighted its humanitarian commitments.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is in South Asia on the Bay of Bengal.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It is surrounded almost entirely by neighbouring India, and shares a small border with Myanmar to its southeast, though it lies very close to Nepal, Bhutan, and China.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The country is divided into three regions.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Most of the country is dominated by the fertile Ganges Delta, the largest river delta in the world.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The northwest and central parts of the country are formed by the Madhupur and the Barind plateaus.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The northeast and southeast are home to evergreen hill ranges.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Ganges delta is formed by the confluence of the Ganges (local name Padma or *Pôdda*), Brahmaputra (Jamuna or *Jomuna*), and Meghna rivers and their tributaries.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Ganges unites with the Jamuna (main channel of the Brahmaputra) and later joins the Meghna, finally flowing into the Bay of Bengal.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is called the "Land of Rivers", as it is home to over 57 trans-boundary rivers, the most of any nation-state.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Water issues are politically complicated since Bangladesh is downstream of India.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is predominantly rich fertile flat land.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Most of it is less than 12 m (39 ft) above sea level, and it is estimated that about 10% of its land would be flooded if the sea level were to rise by 1 m (3.3 ft).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] 12% of the country is covered by hill systems.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The country's haor wetlands are of significance to global environmental science.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The highest point in Bangladesh is the Saka Haphong, located near the border with Myanmar, with an elevation of 1,064 m (3,491 ft).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Previously, either Keokradong or Tazing Dong were considered the highest.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In Bangladesh forest cover is around 14% of the total land area, equivalent to 1,883,400 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, down from 1,920,330 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 1,725,330 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 158,070 hectares (ha).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest 0% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 33% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] For the year 2015, 100% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Straddling the Tropic of Cancer, Bangladesh's climate is tropical, with a mild winter from October to March and a hot, humid summer from March to June.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The country has never recorded an air temperature below 0 °C (32 °F), with a record low of 1.1 °C (34.0 °F) in the northwest city of Dinajpur on 3 February 1905.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] A warm and humid monsoon season lasts from June to October and supplies most of the country's rainfall.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Natural calamities, such as floods, tropical cyclones, tornadoes, and tidal bores occur almost every year, combined with the effects of deforestation, soil degradation and erosion.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The cyclones of 1970 and 1991 were particularly devastating, the latter killing approximately 140,000 people.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In September 1998, Bangladesh saw the most severe flooding in modern history, after which two-thirds of the country went underwater, along with a death toll of 1,000.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] As a result of various international and national level initiatives in disaster risk reduction, the human toll and economic damage from floods and cyclones have come down over the years.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The 2007 South Asian floods ravaged areas across the country, leaving five million people displaced, with a death toll around 500.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is recognised to be one of the countries most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Over the course of a century, 508 cyclones have affected the Bay of Bengal region, 17% of which are believed to have made landfall in Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Natural hazards that come from increased rainfall, rising sea levels, and tropical cyclones are expected to increase as the climate changes, each seriously affecting agriculture, water and food security, human health, and shelter.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It is estimated that by 2050, a three-foot rise in sea levels will inundate some 20% of the land and displace more than 30 million people.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] To address the sea level rise threat in Bangladesh, the Bangladesh Delta Plan 2100 has been launched.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is located in the Indomalayan realm, and lies within four terrestrial ecoregions: Lower Gangetic Plains moist deciduous forests, Mizoram–Manipur–Kachin rain forests, Sundarbans freshwater swamp forests, and Sundarbans mangroves.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Its ecology includes a long sea coastline, numerous rivers and tributaries, lakes, wetlands, evergreen forests, semi evergreen forests, hill forests, moist deciduous forests, freshwater swamp forests and flat land with tall grass.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Bangladesh Plain is famous for its fertile alluvial soil which supports extensive cultivation.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The country is dominated by lush vegetation, with villages often buried in groves of mango, jackfruit, bamboo, betel nut, coconut, and date palm.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The country has up to 6000 species of plant life, including 5000 flowering plants.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Water bodies and wetland systems provide a habitat for many aquatic plants.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Water lilies and lotuses grow vividly during the monsoon season.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The country has 60 wildlife sanctuaries.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is home to most of the Sundarbans, the world's largest mangrove forest, covering an area of 6,000 square kilometres (2,300 sq mi) in the southwest littoral region.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It is divided into three protected sanctuaries: the South, East, and West zones.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The forest is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The northeastern Sylhet region is home to haor wetlands, a unique ecosystem.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It also includes tropical and subtropical coniferous forests, a freshwater swamp forest, and mixed deciduous forests.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The southeastern Chittagong region covers evergreen and semi-evergreen hilly jungles.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Central Bangladesh includes the plainland Sal forest running along with the districts of Gazipur, Tangail, and Mymensingh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Martin's Island is the only coral reef in the country.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh has an abundance of wildlife in its forests, marshes, woodlands, and hills.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The vast majority of animals dwell within a habitat of 150,000 square kilometres (58,000 sq mi).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Bengal tiger, clouded leopard, saltwater crocodile, black panther and fishing cat are among the chief predators in the Sundarbans.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Northern and eastern Bangladesh is home to the Asian elephant, hoolock gibbon, Asian black bear and oriental pied hornbill.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The chital deer are widely seen in southwestern woodlands.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Other animals include the black giant squirrel, capped langur, Bengal fox, sambar deer, jungle cat, king cobra, wild boar, mongooses, pangolins, pythons and water monitors.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh has one of the largest populations of Irrawaddy and Ganges dolphins.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The country has numerous species of amphibians (53), reptiles (139), marine reptiles (19) and marine mammals (5).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Several animals became extinct in Bangladesh during the last century, including the one-horned and two-horned rhinoceros and common peafowl.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The human population is concentrated in urban areas, limiting deforestation to a certain extent.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Rapid urban growth has threatened natural habitats.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The country has widespread environmental issues; pollution of the Dhaleshwari River by the textile industry and shrimp cultivation in Chakaria Sundarbans have both been described by academics as ecocides.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Although many areas are protected under law, some Bangladeshi wildlife is threatened by this growth.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Bangladesh Environment Conservation Act was enacted in 1995.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The government has designated several regions as Ecologically Critical Areas, including wetlands, forests, and rivers.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Sundarbans tiger project and the Bangladesh Bear Project are among the key initiatives to strengthen conservation.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It ratified the Rio Convention on Biological Diversity on 3 May 1994.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] As of 2014, the country was set to revise its National Biodiversity Strategy and Action Plan.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh, by constitution, is a unitary state and a *de jure* representative democracy with a Westminster-style parliamentary system that has universal suffrage.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The government can be divided into three pillars: the executive, the legislative and the judiciary.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] All function to ensure accountability, transparency and checks and balances.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Since its independence, the Awami League (AL) and the Bangladesh Nationalist Party (BNP) have remained two of the most powerful political parties in Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Bangladesh performs in the low range on overall democratic measures, with particular weaknesses in political representation, including credible elections, inclusive suffrage and elected government.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is divided into eight administrative divisions, each named after its headquarters: Barisal (officially *Barishal*), Chittagong (officially *Chattogram*), Dhaka, Khulna, Mymensingh, Rajshahi, Rangpur, and Sylhet.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Divisions are subdivided into districts (*zila*).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh has 64 districts, each subdivided into *upazila* (subdistricts) or *thana*.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The area within each police station, except for those in metropolitan areas, is divided into *unions*, with each union comprising multiple villages.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In the metropolitan areas, police stations are divided into wards, further divided into *mahallas*.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] There are no elected officials at the divisional or district levels, and the administration comprises only government officials.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Direct elections are held in each union (or ward) for a chairperson and several members.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In 1997, Parliament passed legislation reserving three seats (out of 12) in every union for women.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is considered a middle power in global politics.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It plays an important role in the geopolitical affairs of the Indo-Pacific, due to its strategic location between South and Southeast Asia.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh joined the Commonwealth of Nations in 1972 and the United Nations in 1974.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It relies on multilateral diplomacy on issues like climate change, nuclear non-proliferation, trade policy and non-traditional security issues.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh pioneered the creation of SAARC, the preeminent forum for regional diplomacy on the Indian subcontinent.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It joined the OIC in 1974, and is a founding member of the Developing-8.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Recently, Bangladesh has focused on promoting regional trade and transport links with support from the World Bank.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It is also attempting to join ASEAN as one of its top foreign policy goals.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Dhaka hosts the headquarters of BIMSTEC, an organisation that brings together countries dependent on the Bay of Bengal.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Relations with neighbouring Myanmar have been severely strained since 2016–2017, after over 700,000 Rohingya refugees illegally entered Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh's parliament, government, and civil society have been at the forefront of international criticism against Myanmar for military operations against the Rohingya, and have demanded their right of return to Arakan.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh shares an important bilateral and economic relationship with its largest neighbour, India, which is often strained by water politics of the Ganges and the Teesta, and the border killings of Bangladeshi civilians.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh's relationship with Pakistan is problematic, mainly because Pakistan denies the 1971 Bangladesh genocide.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It maintains a warm relationship with China, its largest trading partner and largest arms supplier.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Japan is Bangladesh's largest economic aid provider, and the two have a strategic and economic partnership.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Political relations with Middle Eastern countries are robust.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh receives 59% of its remittances from the Middle East, despite poor working conditions affecting over four million Bangladeshi workers.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh plays a major role in global climate diplomacy as a leader of the Climate Vulnerable Forum.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Bangladesh Armed Forces have inherited the institutional framework of the British military and the British Indian Army.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In 2024, the active personnel strength of the Bangladesh Armed Forces was around 230,000, including the Air Force (21,000) and the Navy (27,000).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In addition to traditional defence roles, the military has supported civil authorities in disaster relief and provided internal security during periods of political unrest.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] For many years, Bangladesh has been the world's largest contributor to UN peacekeeping forces.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The military budget of Bangladesh accounts for 1.3% of GDP, amounting to US$4.3 billion in 2021.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Bangladesh Navy, one of the largest in the Bay of Bengal, includes a fleet of frigates, submarines, corvettes, and other vessels.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Bangladesh Air Force has a small fleet of multi-role combat aircraft.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Most of Bangladesh's military equipment comes from China.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In recent years, Bangladesh and India have increased joint military exercises, high-level visits of military leaders, counter-terrorism cooperation and intelligence sharing.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is vital to ensuring stability and security in northeast India.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh's strategic importance in the eastern subcontinent hinges on its proximity to China, its frontier with Burma, the separation of mainland and northeast India, and its maritime territory in the Bay of Bengal.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In 2002, Bangladesh and China signed a Defense Cooperation Agreement.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The United States has pursued negotiations with Bangladesh on a Status of forces agreement, an Acquisition and Cross-Servicing Agreement and a General Security of Military Information Agreement.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] In 2019, Bangladesh ratified the UN Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Since the colonial period, Bangladesh has had a prominent civil society.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] There are various special interest groups, including non-governmental organisations, human rights organisations, professional associations, chambers of commerce, employers' associations, and trade unions.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The National Human Rights Commission of Bangladesh was set up in 2007.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Notable human rights organisations and initiatives include the Centre for Law and Mediation, Odhikar, the Alliance for Bangladesh Worker Safety, the Bangladesh Environmental Lawyers Association, the Bangladesh Hindu Buddhist Christian Unity Council and the War Crimes Fact Finding Committee.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The world's largest international NGO BRAC is based in Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] There has been concern about the shrinking space for independent civil society in recent years.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Torture is banned by the Constitution of Bangladesh, but is rampantly used by Bangladesh's security forces.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh joined the Convention against Torture in 1998 and enacted its first anti-torture law, the Torture and Custodial Death (Prevention) Act, in 2013.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The first conviction under this law was announced in 2020.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Amnesty International Prisoners of Conscience from Bangladesh have included Saber Hossain Chowdhury and Shahidul Alam.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The widely criticised Digital Security Act was repealed and replaced by the Cyber Security Act in 2023.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The repeal was welcomed by the International Press Institute.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] On International Human Rights Day in December 2021, the United States Department of the Treasury announced sanctions on commanders of the Rapid Action Battalion for extrajudicial killings, torture, and other human rights abuses.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Freedom House has criticised the government for human rights abuses, the crackdown on the opposition, mass media, and civil society through politicised enforcement.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is ranked "partly free" in Freedom House's *Freedom in the World* report, but its press freedom has deteriorated from "free" to "not free" in recent years due to increasing government pressure.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] According to the British Economist Intelligence Unit, the country has a hybrid regime: the third of four rankings in its Democracy Index.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh ranked 96th among 163 countries in the 2022 Global Peace Index.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] According to National Human Rights Commission, 70% of alleged human-rights violations are committed by law-enforcement agencies.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] LGBT rights are frowned upon among social conservatives.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Homosexuality is affected by Section 377 of the Penal Code of Bangladesh, originally enacted by the British colonial government.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The government only recognises the transgender and intersex community known as the Hijra.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] According to the 2023 Global Slavery Index, an estimated 1.2 million people were enslaved in Bangladesh as of 2021, which is among the highest in the world.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Like many developing countries, institutional corruption is an issue of concern for Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh ranked 146th among 180 countries on Transparency International's 2018 Corruption Perceptions Index.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Land administration was the sector with the most bribery in 2015, followed by education, police and water supply.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Anti Corruption Commission was formed in 2004, and was active during the 2006–08 Bangladeshi political crisis, indicting many leading politicians, bureaucrats and businessmen for graft.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is a lower-middle income mixed-market economy.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It has the world's 36th-largest economy by nominal terms, and the 24th-largest by PPP.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh has a labour force of 71.4 million, which is the world's seventh-largest; with an unemployment rate of 3.6% as of 2024.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Its foreign exchange reserves, although depleting, remain the second-highest in South Asia, after India.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh's large diaspora contributed roughly $27 billion in remittances in 2024.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Bangladeshi taka is the national currency.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] As of 2023, the large service sector accounts for about 51.5% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (34.6%), while the agriculture sector is by far the smallest, making up only 11% of total GDP; despite being the largest employment sector, providing roughly half of the total workforce.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Over 84% of the export earnings come from the textile industry.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh is the second-leading garments exporter in the world, and plays a crucial role in the global fast fashion industry, exporting to various Western fashion brands.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It is also a major producer of jute, rice, fish, tea, and flowers.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Other major industries include shipbuilding, pharmaceuticals, steel, electronics and leather goods.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] China is the largest trading partner of Bangladesh, accounting for 15% of the total trade, followed by India; which accounts for 8% of the total trade.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The private sector accounts for 80% of GDP compared to the dwindling role of state-owned companies.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh's economy is dominated by family-owned conglomerates and small and medium-sized businesses.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Some of the largest publicly traded companies in Bangladesh include BEXIMCO, BRAC Bank, BSRM, GPH Ispat, Grameenphone, Summit Group, and Square Pharmaceuticals.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The Dhaka and Chittagong Stock Exchanges are the country's twin capital markets.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Its telecommunications industry is one of the world's fastest growing, with 188.78 million cellphone subscribers at the end of November 2024.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Political instability, high inflation, endemic corruption, insufficient power supplies, and slow implementation of reforms are major challenges to economic growth.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh was ranked 106th in the Global Innovation Index in 2024 and in 2025.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh, a country experiencing daily blackouts several times a day in 2009, achieved 100% electrification by 2022.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It is gradually transitioning to a green economy and has the largest off-grid solar power programme in the world, benefiting 20 million people.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] An electric car called the *Palki* is being developed for production in the country.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Biogas is being used to produce organic fertiliser.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The under-construction Rooppur Nuclear Power Plant, under-construction with assistance from the Russian company Rosatom, will be the first operational nuclear power plant in the country.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Its first unit, out of the two total units, is expected to go into operation in 2025.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh continues to have huge untapped reserves of natural gas, particularly in its maritime territory.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] A lack of exploration and decreasing proven reserves have forced Bangladesh to import LNG from abroad.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Gas shortages were further exacerbated by the Russo-Ukrainian war.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh stopped buying spot price LNG temporarily in July 2022, despite constant load-shedding, due to a steep price hike in the global market.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It restarted buying spot price LNG once again in February 2023 as prices eased.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] While government-owned companies in Bangladesh generate nearly half of Bangladesh's electricity, privately owned companies like the Summit Group and Orion Group are playing an increasingly important role in both generating electricity, and supplying machinery, reactors, and equipment.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh increased electricity production capacity from 5 gigawatts in 2009 to 25.5 gigawatts in 2022.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] It plans to further increase it to 50 gigawatts by 2041.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] US companies like Chevron and General Electric supply around 55% of Bangladesh's domestic natural gas production and are among the largest investors in power projects.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] 80% of Bangladesh's installed gas-fired power generation capacity comes from turbines manufactured in the United States.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The tourism industry is expanding, contributing some 3.02% of total GDP.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Bangladesh's international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $391 million.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The country has three UNESCO World Heritage Sites (the Mosque City, the Buddhist Vihara and the Sundarbans) and seven tentative-list sites.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] The World Travel and Tourism Council (WTTC) reported in 2019 that the travel and tourism industry in Bangladesh directly generated 1,180,500 jobs in 2018 or 1.9% of the country's total employment.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] According to the same report, Bangladesh experiences around 125,000 international tourist arrivals per year.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p01] Domestic spending generated 97.7% of direct travel and tourism gross domestic product (GDP) in 2012.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh had a recorded population of 169.8 million in the 2022 census, which rose to 171.4 million as of 2023.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] It is the eighth-most-populous country in the world, the fifth-most populous country in Asia, and the most densely populated large country in the world, with a headline population density of 1,265 people/km2 as of 2020.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh's total fertility rate (TFR), once among the highest in the world, has experienced a dramatic decline, from 5.5 in 1985 to 3.7 in 1995, down to 1.9 in 2022, which is below the sub-replacement fertility of 2.1.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Most of the population live in rural areas, with only 40% of the population living in urban areas as of 2023.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh has a median age of roughly 28 years, with 26% of the total population aged 14 or younger, and merely 6% aged 65 and above as of 2023.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh is an ethnically and culturally homogeneous society, as Bengalis form 99% of the population.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Adivasi population includes the Chakmas, Marmas, Santhals, Mros, Tanchangyas, Bawms, Tripuris, Khasis, Khumis, Kukis, Garos, and Bisnupriya Manipuris.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Chittagong Hill Tracts region experienced unrest and an insurgency from 1975 to 1997 in an autonomy movement by its indigenous people.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Although a peace accord was signed in 1997, the region remains militarised.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Urdu-speaking stranded Pakistanis were given citizenship by the Supreme Court in 2008.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh also hosts over 700,000 Rohingya refugees since 2017, giving it one of the largest refugee populations in the world.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh's capital Dhaka and the largest city and is overseen by two city corporations that manage between them the northern and southern parts of the city.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] There are 13 city corporations which hold mayoral elections: Dhaka South, Dhaka North, Chittagong, Comilla, Khulna, Mymensingh, Sylhet, Rajshahi, Barisal, Rangpur, Gazipur, Bogura and Narayanganj.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Altogether there are 506 urban centres in Bangladesh which 43 cities have a population of more than 100,000.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The official and predominant language of Bangladesh is Bengali, which is spoken by more than 99% of the population as their native language.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bengali is described as a dialect continuum where there are various dialects spoken throughout the country.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] There is a diglossia in which much of the population can understand or speak in Standard Colloquial Bengali, and in their regional dialect or language variety.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] These include Chittagonian which is spoken in the southeastern region of Chittagong, Noakhali spoken in the southern district of Noakhali and Sylheti spoken in the northeastern region of Sylhet.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] English plays an important role in Bangladesh's judicial and educational affairs, due to the country's history as part of the British Empire.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] It is widely spoken and commonly understood, and is taught as a compulsory subject in all schools, colleges and universities, while the English-medium educational system is widely attended.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Tribal languages, although increasingly endangered, include the Chakma language, another native Eastern Indo-Aryan language, spoken by the Chakma people.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Others are Garo, Meitei, Kokborok and Rakhine.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Among the Austroasiatic languages, the most spoken is the Santali language, native to the Santal people.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The stranded Pakistanis and some sections of the Old Dhakaites often use Urdu as their native tongue.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Still, the usage of the latter remains highly reproached.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Islam is the state religion of Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] However, the constitution also upholds secularism and ensures equal rights for all religions.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Every citizen has the freedom to practice any religion.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Islam the largest religion across the country, being followed by about 91.1% of the population.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The vast majority of Bangladeshi citizens are Bengali Muslims, adhering to Sunni Islam.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The country is the third-most populous Muslim-majority state in the world and has the fourth-largest overall Muslim population.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bengali Hindus form the country's second-largest religious minority and the third-largest Hindu community in the world.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] According to the 2022 census Hindus form 7.95% of the total population.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] In the 2011 census, Hindus formed 8.54% of the population.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Buddhism is the third-most followed religion, adhered to by merely 0.6% of the population.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladeshi Buddhists are concentrated among the tribal ethnic groups in the Chittagong Hill Tracts and by the Bengali Buddhist minority across coastal Chittagong, who mostly follow the Theravada school.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Christianity is the fourth-largest religion at 0.3%, followed mainly by a small Bengali Christian minority.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] 0.1% of the population practices other religions such as Animism or is irreligious.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The constitution states that all children shall receive free and compulsory education.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Education in Bangladesh is overseen by the Ministry of Education.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Ministry of Primary and Mass Education is responsible for implementing policy for primary education and state-funded schools at a local level.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Primary and secondary education is compulsory, and is financed by the state and free of charge in public schools.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh has a literacy rate of 76% as of 2021: 79% for males and 71.9% for females.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Its educational system is three-tiered and heavily subsidised, with the government operating many schools at the primary, secondary and higher secondary levels and subsidising many private schools.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] However, government expenditure in education remains among the lowest in the world, at only 1.8% of the total GDP.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The education system is divided into five levels: primary (first to fifth grade), junior secondary (sixth to eighth grade), secondary (ninth and tenth grade), higher secondary (11th and 12th grade), and tertiary which is university level.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Primary level students have to pass the Primary Education Completion (PEC) exam to proceed to junior secondary.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The junior secondary students then give the Junior School Certificate (JSC) exam to get enrolled in ninth grade, while tenth-grade students have to pass the Secondary School Certificate (SSC) exam to proceed to eleventh grade.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Lastly, students have to pass the Higher Secondary Certificate (HSC) exam at grade twelve to apply for higher education or universities.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Universities are three general types: public (government-owned and funded by the University Grants Commission), private (privately owned universities) and international (operated and funded by international organisations).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The country has 55 public, 115 private and 2 international universities.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] National University is the second-largest university in the world by enrolment.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The University of Dhaka, established in 1921, is the oldest public university.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] BUET is the premiere university for engineering education.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The University of Chittagong, established in 1966, has the largest campus.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] BUP is the largest public university affiliated with the armed forces.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Dhaka College, established in 1841, is among the oldest educational institutes in the Indian subcontinent.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Medical education is provided by 39 government, 6 armed force and 68 private medical colleges.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] All medical colleges are affiliated with the Ministry of Health and Family Welfare.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] North South University is often viewed as the leading private University of the nation.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh, by the constitution, guarantees healthcare services as a fundamental right to all of its citizens.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Ministry of Health and Family Welfare is the largest institutional healthcare provider in Bangladesh, and contains two divisions: Health Service Division and Medical Education And Family Welfare Division.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] However, healthcare facilities in Bangladesh are considered less than adequate, although they have improved as the economy has grown and poverty levels have decreased significantly.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh faces a severe health workforce crisis, as formally trained providers make up a small percentage of the total health workforce.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Significant deficiencies in the treatment practices of village doctors persist, with widespread harmful and inappropriate drug prescribing.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh's poor healthcare system suffers from severe underfunding from the government.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] As of 2021, some 2.36% of total GDP was attributed to healthcare, and domestic general government spending on healthcare was 16.88% of the total budget, while out-of-pocket expenditures made up the vast majority of the total budget, totalling roughly 73%.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Domestic private health expenditure was about 75.48% of the total healthcare expenditure.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] There were only 5.3 doctors per 10,000 people, and about six physicians and six nurses per 1,000 people, while the number of hospital beds is 9 per 1,000.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The specialist surgical workforce was only 3 per 100,000 people, and there were about 5 community health workers per 1,000 people.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Roughly 60% of the population had access to drinking water in 2022.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] In 2002, it was estimated that half of the drinking water was polluted with arsenic, exceeding levels of 10 micrograms per litre.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh is crippled with one of the worst air qualities in the world, mostly concentrated in the densely populated urban areas, especially the capital Dhaka and its metropolitan area.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The World Bank estimated that roughly 80,000–90,000 deaths occurred in Bangladesh due to the drastic effects of air pollution in 2019.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] It was second-leading cause of death and disability, costing the country roughly 4–4.4% of its total GDP.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] As of 2022, the overall life expectancy in Bangladesh at birth was 74 years (72 years for males and 76 years for females).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] It has a comparably high infant mortality rate (24 per 1,000 live births) and child mortality rate (29 per 1,000 live births).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] As of 2020, maternal mortality remains high, clocking at 123 per 100,000 live births.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh is a key source market for medical tourism for various countries, mainly India, due to its citizens dissatisfaction and distrust over their own healthcare system.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The main causes of death are coronary artery disease, stroke, and chronic respiratory disease; comprising 62% and 60% of all adult male and female deaths, respectively.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Malnutrition is a major and persistent problem in Bangladesh, mainly affecting the rural regions, more than half of the population suffers from it.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Severe acute malnutrition affects 450,000 children, while nearly 2 million children have moderate acute malnutrition.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] For children under the age of five, 52% are affected by anemia, 41% are stunted, 16% are wasted, and 36% are underweight.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] A quarter of women are underweight and around 15% have short stature, while over half also suffer from anemia.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh was ranked 84th out of the 127 countries listed in the 2024 Global Hunger Index.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Traditional festivals include Pahela Baishakh (Bengali New Year), which is the major festival of Bengali culture; with widespread festivities.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Pohela Falgun coincides with Valentine's Day, and is celebrated with a display of music, dance and other cultural activities.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Other festivals include Nabonno and Poush Parbon, which celebrate new harvests of crops.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Shakrain is an annual celebration, observed by flying kites, occurring at the end of Poush, the ninth month of the Bengali calendar.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The festival coincides with Makar Sankranti celebrated in India and Nepal.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Among religious festivals, the two biggest festivals of the Muslim majority are Eid al-Fitr, which marks the end of the month of Ramadan—and Eid al-Adha, which is the festival of sacrifice.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Both Eids are celebrated with the longest streak of national holidays.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Other Muslim festivals include Mawlid (Eid-e-Milad Un Nabi), Ashura on the tenth day of Muharram, Chaand Raat, and Shab-e-Barat, Shab-e-Meraj, Shab-e-Qadr during Ramadan and Bishwa Ijtema.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The most celebrated Hindu festival is Durga Puja.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Other major Hindu festivals include Krishna Janmashtami, Kali Puja, Saraswati Puja, and Ratha Yatra.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The biggest festival of the Buddhists across the country is Buddha Purnima, which marks the birth of Gautama Buddha.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Among Christians, Christmas, known as Boro Din, and Easter are the most widely celebrated .
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Patriotic national festivals include the Language Movement Day, which is celebrated on 21 February in remembrance of the martyrs of the 1952 Bengali language movement.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] It was declared as International Mother Language Day by UNESCO in 1999.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Independence Day is celebrated on 26 March to commemorate the proclamation of independence from Pakistan.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Victory Day is celebrated on 16 December to celebrate the victory in the Bangladesh Liberation War.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Public gatherings are observed at the Shaheed Minar and National Martyrs' Memorial during the three latter festivals to pay homage to the fallen martyrs.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bengali literature forms an important part of Bengali culture.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Charyapada poems dating back to the 10th to 12th centuries are the oldest extant examples of the Bengali language.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] During the Bengal Sultanate, medieval Bengali writers were influenced by Arabic and Persian literature.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Milestones of the medieval age include the Mangal-Kāvyas.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Vaishnava Padavali movement was led by writers such as Vidyapati, Chandidas, Govindadas and Balarama Dasa.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] *Shreekrishna Kirtana* written by Chandidas marked a particular height of poetic achievement since the Charyapadas.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Other important works include Krittibas Ojha's translation of the *Ramayana*, Kashiram Das' translation of the *Mahabharata*, and Maladhar Basu's translation of the *Bhagavata*.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Writers such as Bipradas Pipilai, Vijay Gupta, Shah Muhammad Sagir, Zainuddin and Abdul Hakim were important figures.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Alaol, considered a bard, is a prolific poet of medieval period.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Bengal Renaissance from the late 18th century to the early 20th century had a profound effect on modern Bengali literature.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Michael Madhusudan Dutt invented the blank verse in Bengali literature.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Mir Mosharraf Hossain was the first prominent Bengali Muslim writer.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Lalon, a fakir practising Sufism and sādhanā influenced the bauls.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Sarat Chandra Chattopadhyay wrote about the characteristics of the Bengali society.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Rabindranath Tagore was the first Asian and non-European laureate of the Nobel Prize in Literature.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Kazi Nazrul Islam was a revolutionary poet who espoused political rebellion against colonialism and fascism.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Jibanananda Das was the most recognised Bengali poet after Tagore and Nazrul.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Begum Rokeya is regarded as the pioneer feminist writer of Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Syed Mujtaba Ali is noted for his cosmopolitan views.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Jasimuddin was a renowned pastoral poet, popularly called *Palli Kabi* (folk poet).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Farrukh Ahmad is considered the poet of the "Islamic Renaissance".
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Shamsur Rahman and Al Mahmud are considered two of the greatest Bangladeshi poets to have emerged in the late 20th century.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Ahmed Sofa is regarded as the most important intellectual in the post-independence era.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Sufia Kamal was a major feminist writer.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Humayun Ahmed was the most popular author in post-Independence Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Shahidul Zahir was widely acclaimed for his usage of magical realism.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Other major writers include Akhteruzzaman Elias, Shawkat Osman and Syed Shamsul Haq.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Selina Hossain is a prolific female author in the modern era.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Muhammad Zafar Iqbal is a pioneer science fiction writer.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Anisul Hoque is a popular contemporary literary figure.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The annual Ekushey Book Fair and Dhaka Lit Fest, organised by the Bangla Academy, are among the largest literary festivals in South Asia.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The architecture of Bangladesh is intertwined with that of the Bengal region and the broader Indian subcontinent.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] It is influenced by the country's culture, religion and history.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Hindu and Buddhist architectural remnants have been found in Mahasthangarh, which dates back to the 3rd century BCE.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Nandipada and Swastika symbols have been found on stone querns in the Wari-Bateshwar ruins, which indicate the presence of Hinduism in the area during the Iron Age—from 400 to 100 BCE.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Somapura Mahavihara built under the rule of the Buddhist Pala Empire in the 8th century is an outstanding example of the pre-Islamic era.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Other Buddhist vihāras include Shalban Bihar in Mainamati and Bikrampur Vihara in Bikrampur.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Recent excavations have also uncovered new evidence of pre-Islamic smaller temples which served the Hindu, Buddhist and Jain populations of the area.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Indo-Islamic architecture can be seen from the 13th century, especially in the unique mosque architecture of the Bengal Sultanate, an example being the Sixty Dome Mosque among others in the Mosque City of Bagerhat—which is a UNESCO World Heritage Site.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Mughal Bengal saw the spread of Mughal architecture in the region.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Examples in Dhaka include the Bara Katra and Choto Katra in Old Dhaka, the Sat Gambuj Mosque in Mohammadpur and the Musa Khan Mosque in Curzon Hall.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Notable Mughal-era forts include the Lalbagh Fort in Old Dhaka, the Idrakpur Fort in Munshiganj—and the Hajiganj Fort and the Sonakanda Fort in Narayanganj, respectively.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Kantajew Temple and Dhakeshwari Temple are excellent examples of late medieval Hindu temple architecture.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bengali vernacular architecture is noted for pioneering the bungalow.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Panam Nagar in Sonargaon exhibits architectural influence from the Sultanate, Mughal, British and hybrid colonial traditions.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Indo-Saracenic architecture flourished during the British Raj, examples include the Curzon Hall of the University of Dhaka, the Chittagong Court Building, Rangpur Town Hall and Rajshahi College.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The zamindar gentry built many palaces in the latter style, including the Ahsan Manzil, the Baliati Zamnidar Bari, the Tajhat Palace, the Rose Garden Palace, the Dighapatia Palace, the Puthia Rajbari, Natore Rajbari and the Mohera Zamindar Bari.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Muzharul Islam is considered to be a pioneer of modernist movement in Bangladesh and South Asia.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Louis Kahn is a notable foreign architect who designed the National Parliament Building in Sher-e-Bangla Nagar.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The recorded history of art in Bangladesh can be traced to the 3rd century BCE, when terracotta sculptures were made in the region.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] In classical antiquity, notable sculptural Hindu, Jain, and Buddhist art developed in the Pala Empire and the Sena dynasty.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Bengal Sultanate saw Islamic art evolve since the 14th century.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] During the Mughal rule, Jamdani, a unique design on fine muslin; was woven on Persian motifs in Dhaka.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] It was classified by UNESCO as an Intangible cultural heritage in 2013.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh also produces the Rajshahi silk, a fine silk renowned for its softness and ability to create sophisticated designs.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Ivory, brass and pottery has deep roots in Bangladeshi culture.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Nakshi Kantha, a centuries-old embroidery tradition for quilts in Bengal, is made throughout Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The modern art movement in Bangladesh took shape in post-independence East Bengal, especially with the pioneering works of Zainul Abedin.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Other leading painters include SM Sultan, Mohammad Kibria, Safiuddin Ahmed, Shahabuddin Ahmed, Kanak Chanpa Chakma, Qayyum Chowdhury, Rashid Choudhury, Quamrul Hassan, Rafiqun Nabi and Syed Jahangir.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Novera Ahmed is the pioneer of modernist sculpture in Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Other eminent sculptors include Nitun Kundu, Syed Abdullah Khalid, Hamiduzzaman Khan, Shamim Sikder, Ferdousi Priyabhashini and Abdur Razzaque.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The annual Mangal Shobhajatra (Bengali New Year parade) organised by the Faculty of Fine Arts of the University of Dhaka on Pohela Boishakh was enlisted as an Intangible cultural heritage by UNESCO in 2016.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Photography as a form of art has seen rapid growth in the 21st century.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Chobi Mela, held biennially, is considered the largest photography festival in Asia.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Lungi is the most common informal clothing for men, while kurta (*panjabi*) and pajama are worn by men on festivals and holidays.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Domestically tailored suits, neckties and pants are customarily worn by men at formal events, and the traditional sherwani and churidar are worn along with the turban in weddings.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Women commonly wear the shalwar kameez accompanied by orna; while sari is worn on more formal events.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Theatre in Bangladesh includes various forms with a history dating back to the 4th century CE.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] It includes narrative forms, song and dance forms, supra-personae forms, performances with scroll paintings, puppet theatre and processional forms.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Jatra is the most popular form of Bengali folk theatre.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Apart from the various forms of Indian classical dances, including the *Kathakali*, *Bharatanatyam*, Odissi and Manipuri dances–native dance traditions have formed across the country.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Music of Bangladesh can be classed into classical, light-classical, devotional, and popular.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Classical music in Bangladesh is represented by the common forms of devotional music across the Indian subcontinent; such as the Hindustani classical music genre dhrupad and khayal.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Other major forms include qawwali and kirtan.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Rabindra Sangeet and Nazrul Sangeet retain their popularity.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Native folk music features the baul mystical tradition, which was popularised by Lalon in the 18th century, and is listed by UNESCO as a Masterpiece of Intangible Cultural Heritage.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Other native lyric-based forms of folk music include bhatiali, bhawaiya, dhamail, kavigan, jarigan, sari gan, marfati, and gombhira.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Folk music is accompanied by instruments such as the ektara, dotara, dhol, bansuri (a type of flute), mandira, khanjani, sarinda, khamak, dugdugi, juri, jhunjhuni and majira (a type of cymbal).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh has a rich tradition of Indian classical music, which uses instruments like the sitar, tabla, sarod, and santoor.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Musical organisations and schools such as the Bangladesh Shilpakala Academy and Chhayanaut have played significant roles in preserving the traditions of Bengali folk music.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Sabina Yasmin and Runa Laila are considered two of the greatest female playback singers in the country.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Andrew Kishore, another leading playback singer, is considered the "King of Playback".
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Azam Khan, nicknamed the "Pop Samrat" and the "Rock Guru", is a founding figure of Bangladeshi rock.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Musicians such as Ayub Bachchu and James have also gained nationwide popularity.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Shayan Chowdhury Arnob has been an influential figure in indie rock.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Popular pop singers in the 21st century include Habib Wahid and Tahsan Rahman Khan.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Influential heavy metal include Artcell and Warfaze.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The history of press in Bangladesh dates back to 1860, when the first printing press was established in Dhaka.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The media in Bangladesh is diverse, competitive, commercial and profitable.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Prominent news agencies in Bangladesh include Bangladesh Sangbad Sangstha (BSS) and Bdnews24.com.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Television is the most popular form of media consumption.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh Television (BTV) is the sole state-owned television network with nationwide coverage.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Private television networks include ATN Bangla, Channel I, NTV, RTV, Ekushey TV, Ekattor TV, Jamuna TV and Somoy TV.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Print media is the second-most widely consumed, and newspapers are privately owned and outspoken, including The Daily Star, Dhaka Tribune, The Financial Express, Bangladesh Pratidin, Kaler Kantho, Prothom Alo, The Daily Ittefaq and Jugantor.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh Betar is the lone state-run radio service.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Radio Foorti, Radio Today, Radio Aamar and ABC Radio were popular privately owned radio stations; popularity of radio has declined significantly.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Popular foreign media include BBC News (BBC Bangla), CNN, VOA and Al Jazeera.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Indian television drama in particular has established a "cultural hegemony" over Bangladeshi satellite television.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Freedom of the press remains a major concern due to government attempts at censorship and the harassment of journalists.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh ranked 152nd out of the 180 countries listed in the 2026 World Press Freedom Index, among the lowest rankings in the world.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The cinema of Bangladesh dates back to a screening of a bioscope in 1898.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Nawabs of Dhaka patronised the production of several silent films from the 1900s.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Picture House, the first permanent cinema in Dhaka, began its operation during the year between 1913 and 1914.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] *Sukumari* (The Good Girl), released in 1929, was the first film produced in Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] *The Last Kiss*, the first full-length feature film, was released in 1931.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] By 1947, a total of 80 cinemas were listed.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The first Bengali-language film in East Pakistan, *Mukh O Mukhosh* (Face and Mask), was released in 1956.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] *Akash ar Mati* (Sky and Earth), released in 1959, was the second film as such.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Bangladesh Film Development Corporation was founded in Dhaka as the East Pakistan Film Development Corporation in 1957–1958, as the full-service film production studio.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Zahir Raihan made various influential films throughout the period, notably *Kokhono Asheni* in 1961, *Shangam* in 1964 (the first colour film in Pakistan), and *Jibon Theke Neowa* in 1970.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The film industry in Dhaka positioned itself as the base for a Bengali Muslim cinema from the 1960s and onwards.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The first movie post-Independence, *Ora Egaro Jon*, was directed by Chashi Nazrul Islam and released in 1972.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] At the industry's peak, about 80 movies were produced each year between 1996 and 2003, a number which has constantly declined thereafter.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Prominent directors include Khan Ataur Rahman, Alamgir Kabir, Amjad Hossain, Humayun Ahmed, Morshedul Islam, Tanvir Mokammel, Tareque Masud, Salahuddin Lavlu and Enamul Karim Nirjhar.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Tareque Masud was honoured by FIPRESCI at the 2002 Cannes Film Festival for his film *Matir Moina* (The Clay Bird).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Film societes have played a crucial role in the development of cinema in Bangladesh.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladeshi cuisine, formed by the nation's geographic location, climate, and history—is rich and diverse.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The staple dish is white rice, which along with fish, forms the culinary base.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Varieties of leaf vegetables, potatoes, gourds and lentils (dal) also play an important role.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Curries of beef, mutton, chicken and duck are commonly consumed, along with multiple types of bhortas (mashed vegetables), *bhajis* (stir fried vegetables) and tarkaris (curried vegetables).
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Mughal-influenced dishes include kormas, kalias, biryanis, pulaos, teharis and khichuris.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Among the various used spices, turmeric, fenugreek, nigella, coriander, anise, cardamom and chili powder are widely used; a famous spice mix is the panch phoron.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Condiments and herbs used include red onions, green chillies, garlic, ginger, cilantro, and mint.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Coconut milk, mustard paste, mustard seeds, mustard oil, ghee, achars and chutneys are also widely used in the cuisine.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Fish is the main source of protein, owing to the country's riverine geography, and it is often eaten with its roe.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The hilsa is the national fish and is immensely popular.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Other highly consumed fishes include rohu, pangas, and tilapia.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Lobsters, shrimps and dried fish (*shutki*) also play an important role in the local cuisines.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] In Chittagong, dishes involving beef include kala bhuna and mezban, the latter being a traditionally popular feast, featuring the serving of *mezbani gosht*, a hot and spicy beef curry.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] In Sylhet, the *shatkora* lemons are used to marinate dishes, a notable one is beef hatkora.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Among the tribal communities in the Chittagong Hill Tracts, cooking with bamboo shoots is popular.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Khulna is known for using *chui jhal* (piper chaba) in its meat-based dishes.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] *Kalai ruti*, a type of rustic flatbread, is widely consumed in Chapai Nawabganj of Rajshahi.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh has a vast spread of desserts, including sweets such as the *rôshogolla*, *roshmalai*, *chomchom*, *sondesh*, *mishti doi* and *kalojaam*, and *jilapi*.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Pithas are traditional boiled desserts made with rice or fruits.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Halwa, shemai and falooda, the latter two being a variation of vermicelli; are popular desserts during religious festivities.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Ruti, naan, paratha, luchi and bakarkhani are the main local breads.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Hot milk tea is the most commonly consumed beverage in the country, being at the centre of group conversations.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Borhani, mattha and lassi are popular traditionally consumed beverages.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Kebabs are widely popular, particularly seekh kebab, chapli kebab, shami kebab, chicken tikka and shashlik, along with various types of *chaaps*.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Popular street foods include chotpoti, jhal muri, *shingara*, samosa and fuchka.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] In rural Bangladesh, several traditional indigenous sports such as Kabaddi, Boli Khela, Lathi Khela and Nouka Baich remain fairly popular.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] While Kabaddi is the national sport, Cricket is arguably the most popular sport in the country.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The national cricket team participated in their first Cricket World Cup in 1999 and the following year was granted Test cricket status.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh reached the quarter-final of the 2015 Cricket World Cup, the semi-final of the 2017 ICC Champions Trophy and they reached the final of the Asia Cup 3 times – in 2012, 2016, and 2018.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Shakib Al Hasan is widely regarded as one of the greatest all-rounders in the history of the sport.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] In 2020, the Bangladesh national under-19 cricket team won the men's Under-19 Cricket World Cup.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Bangladesh national under-19 cricket team also won the U-19 Asia cup in 2023 and 2024 consecutively.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] In 2018, the Bangladesh women's national cricket team won the 2018 Women's Twenty20 Asia Cup.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Football is the second-most popular sport in Bangladesh, following cricket.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The first instance of a national football team was the emergence of the Shadhin Bangla football team during the liberation war of 1971.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] On 25 July 1971, the team's captain, Zakaria Pintoo, became the first person to hoist the Bangladesh flag on foreign land before their match in neighbouring India.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Following independence, the national football team made its debut in 1973 and eventually achieved the feat of participating in the AFC Asian Cup (1980), becoming only the second South Asian team to do so.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh's most notable achievements in football include the 2003 SAFF Gold Cup and 1999 South Asian Games.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The Bangladesh women's national football team won the SAFF Women's Championship consecutively in 2022 and 2024.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh archers Ety Khatun and Roman Sana won several gold medals winning all the 10 archery events (both individual and team events) in the 2019 South Asian Games.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] The National Sports Council regulates 42 sporting federations.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Bangladesh has five grandmasters in chess.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Among them, Niaz Murshed was the first grandmaster in South Asia.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] In 2010, mountain climber Musa Ibrahim became the first Bangladeshi climber to conquer Mount Everest.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Wasfia Nazreen is the first Bangladeshi climber to climb the Seven Summits and the K2.
[src:archidendron-jiringa/bangladesh-p02] Babar Ali becomes the first Bangladeshi to climb Mount Makalu in May 2026.
